A CI/CD pipeline (Continuous Integration / Continuous Delivery/Deployment) is the backbone of 
modern DevOps. It automates the process of building, testing, and deploying applications so 
teams can deliver software faster and more reliably.Let me break it down for you with 
explanation and commands/examples:
🔑 CI/CD Pipeline Stages
Source (Code Commit)

Developers push code to GitHub/GitLab/Bitbucket.

Pipeline is triggered via webhook or polling.

Example (Git command):
git push origin main
Build

Code is compiled and dependencies are installed.

Example (Maven build in Jenkins):
stage('Build') {
  steps {
    sh 'mvn clean compile'
  }
}
Test

Unit tests, integration tests, and automated QA checks run.

Example (JUnit with Maven):
stage('Test') {
  steps {
    sh 'mvn test'
  }
}
Package

Application is packaged into an artifact (JAR, WAR, Docker image).

Example (Docker build):
docker build -t myapp:latest .
Deploy

Artifact is deployed to servers, containers, or cloud platforms.

Example (Kubernetes deployment):
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Monitor

Logs and metrics are tracked via CloudWatch, Prometheus, or Grafana.

Example (CloudWatch logs query):
aws logs get-log-events --log-group-name MyAppLogs --log-stream-name Stream1
⚙️ Tools Commonly Used
Jenkins / GitHub Actions / GitLab CI → Pipeline orchestration

Maven / Gradle / npm → Build tools

JUnit / Selenium / PyTest → Testing frameworks

Docker / Kubernetes → Containerization & orchestration

AWS CloudWatch / Prometheus → Monitoring